---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import CatalogueTable from "../components/CatalogueTable.astro";
import HeroViz from "../components/HeroViz.astro";
import { loadCatalogue, validationLevelCounts } from "../lib/catalogue";

const entries = loadCatalogue();
const levelCounts = validationLevelCounts();
const v0 = levelCounts["V0"] ?? 0;
// Levels above the V0 floor, in descending order, rendered as "N at Vk".
const aboveV0 = (["V5", "V4", "V3", "V2", "V1"] as const)
  .filter((lvl) => (levelCounts[lvl] ?? 0) > 0)
  .map((lvl) => `${levelCounts[lvl]} at ${lvl}`);
// Data-driven census for the "What's here" section, so the prose can't go
// stale as the synced catalogue grows (it started as ~30 Earth-Mars rows and
// now spans five planetary systems).
const classCounts: Record<string, number> = {};
for (const e of entries) {
  const k = e.orbit_class ?? "cycler";
  classCounts[k] = (classCounts[k] ?? 0) + 1;
}
const nonHelio = entries.filter((e) => e.primary && e.primary !== "Sun").length;
---
<Base title="Home" description="cyclers.space — an open, validated catalogue of planetary cycler trajectories.">
  <HeroViz />

  <p>
    A public, reproducible catalogue of <strong>planetary cycler trajectories</strong> —
    repeating orbits that shuttle between two or more bodies without stopping, proposed as
    the backbone of interplanetary transport architectures. It spans the classic Earth-Mars
    and Earth-Venus-Mars routes and their moon-to-moon cousins in the Earth-Moon, Jovian,
    Saturnian, and Uranian systems.
  </p>

  <p>
    Each entry is sourced from the published literature and shown with its
    <a href="/about/#validation-levels">validation level</a>, V∞ signature, orbital elements, and
    primary citation. All numerical values trace back to a specific table, page, or equation in a
    cited paper. Most entries are <span class="vlevel">V0</span> — literature-sourced, not yet
    independently re-derived by the upstream
    <a href="https://github.com/Bwooce/cyclers">cyclerfinder</a> ({v0} at V0{aboveV0.length > 0
      ? `, ${aboveV0.join(", ")}`
      : ""}). Higher levels populate as the finder's cross-validation gauntlet (the Forge pipeline)
    closes loops on each entry — a level is assigned only when recorded, mechanical test evidence
    earns it.
  </p>

  <h2>Five kinds, and what they cost</h2>
  <p>
    Not every "cycler" is the same. A true <strong>cycler</strong> repeats forever (a railway
    line in space); a <strong>quasi-cycler</strong> repeats for a bounded window; a
    <strong>precursor</strong> places a vehicle onto one; a <strong>tour</strong> runs once to a
    destination (most flown missions); and a <strong>resonant PO</strong> repeats forever but
    never meets the body it would serve. And the railway itself is never quite free: cyclers span a
    spectrum from <strong>ballistic</strong> (no deterministic engine burns in the idealised model —
    e.g. the Earth–Mars <a href="/cycler/mcconaghy-2006-em-k2/">S1L1</a> at ~10&nbsp;m/s over 30&nbsp;yr)
    to <strong>powered</strong> (the <a href="/cycler/aldrin-classic-em-k1-outbound/">Aldrin cycler</a>
    at ~1.5–2&nbsp;km/s every 15&nbsp;yr). None is truly zero for all time — real planetary geometry,
    sunlight, and navigation always cost a little.
    <a href="/about/#cycler-types">What the kinds mean →</a>&nbsp;·&nbsp;
    <a href="/about/#cycler-cost">the maintenance-ΔV bands →</a>
  </p>

  <h2>Catalogue ({entries.length} entries)</h2>
  <p class="muted">
    Filter by encounter body. Click a column header to sort. Click a name for the full record.
  </p>

  <CatalogueTable entries={entries} />

  <h2>What's here, what isn't</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Here:</strong> {entries.length} entries — {classCounts["cycler"] ?? 0} strict
      cyclers, {classCounts["quasi_cycler"] ?? 0} quasi-cyclers,
      {classCounts["precursor_mga"] ?? 0} precursors, {classCounts["mga_tour"] ?? 0} tours,
      and {classCounts["resonant_po"] ?? 0} resonant PO. The largest blocks are the Russell
      2004/2006 Earth-Mars ballistic-cycler census (~220 rows) and the Russell-Strange 2009
      moon-to-moon cycler tables (32 rows); alongside them sit the Aldrin classic E-M cycler,
      Niehoff VISIT-1/2, the McConaghy SnLm two-synodic taxonomy, the Jones 2017 V-E-M
      triples, the Sanchez Net 2022 "Pony Express" pair, the Hollister-Menning 1970
      Earth-Venus swing-by, and {nonHelio} non-heliocentric entries (Earth-Moon, Jovian,
      Saturnian, Uranian, Pluto-Charon). Regimes range from strictly ballistic to powered
      and low-thrust — see the <a href="/about/#cycler-cost">maintenance-ΔV bands</a>.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Now live:</strong> real-ephemeris geometric-match
      <a href="/launch-windows/">launch windows</a>
      for each ballistic, Earth-touching cycler — astropy + JPL DE440 + Lambert solve at
      each grid date. Dates are real and verifiable, and each window now also shows
      C<sub>3</sub> at departure, time-of-flight to first encounter, and (for closed
      Earth-Mars cyclers) a computed maintenance-ΔV budget.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Out of scope (for now):</strong> interactive Tisserand-graph exploration
      (tracked in the upstream project's spec, §15). 3-D orbit visualisation has shipped:
      the front-page hero gallery above, and each catalogue entry's own per-cycler 3D view.
    </li>
  </ul>
</Base>
